12- Wk19 Small and large bowel 

Saturday, September 23, 2017 

1:00 PM 

Identify the divisions of the small bowel- duodenum, jejunum, ileum 

 

Duodenum 

The descending and inferior horizontal parts of the duodenum are retroperitoneal, whilst the superior and ascending parts are intraperitoneal.  

 

 

The major junctions to note at the duodenum are the major duodenal papilla/ampulla of Vater (meeting of bile duct and a pancreatic duct), and the minor duodenal papilla (minor pancreatic duct branch). Also to note is the duodenal-jejunal flexure. The duodenum spans from around L2-L3.  

 

 

Blood supply to the proximal end of the duodenum (before major papilla) is supplied by the gastroduodenal artery (from celiac trunk), and the distal end is supplied by the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery (from superior mesenteric).  

 

Jejunum and ileum 

The jejunum takes up first 60% of the 6m long small intestine, and the ileum takes up 40%. There is no demarcation between the jejunum and ileum, but there is a gradual transition from jejunum to ileum involving the decreased density of plicae.  

 

Blood supply to the jejunum and ileum occurs through the mesenteries, from the superior mesenteric artery. The superior mesenteric artery splits into around 20 branches which anastomose to from loops called arcades. From the arcades, long and straight arteries (vasa recta) extend to supply the intestine. The vasa recta become shorter as we move toward the ileum end of the small intestine.  

 

Identify the divisions of the large intestine- cecum, ascending, transverse, descending, and sigmoid colon 

The ileum terminates at the ileo-cecal valve/junction. The large bowel is around 1.5m long, and is composed of the cecum, appendix, ascending colon, transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, rectum and anus.  

 

The ascending and descending colon are retroperitoneal. The anus and lower 2/3 of rectum are also retroperitoneal. The rest are intraperitoneal. 

 

 

The haustra of the colon are the small pouches caused by sacculation (sac formation). This is caused by the taenie coli longitudinal muscle, which is shorter than 1.5 meters and thus pulls the intestines to form repeated pouches. Note that the omental appendices are filled with fat.  

 

Blood supply 

The ascending colon and first 2/3 of the transverse colon are derived from the midgut, whilst the rest is derived from the hindgut.  

 

Midgut-derived structures are generally supplied by the superior mesenteric artery. The ascending colon receives arterial supply from the ileocolic and right colic arteries (from superior mesenteric), and the transverse colon is supplied by the right colic, middle colic (from superior mesenteric) and left colic (from inferior mesenteric) arteries.  

 

The descending colon receives arterial blood form the left colic artery, and the sigmoid colon receives blood from the sigmoid arteries (from inferior mesenteric).  

 

The ascending colon is drained by the ileocolic and right colic veins, the transverse colon is drained by the superior mesenteric vein, the descending colon is drained by the left colic vein, and the sigmoid colon is drained by the sigmoid veins (both into inferior mesenteric).  

 

The terminal vessels of the superior mesenteric and inferior mesenteric arteries anastomose with each other to form a continuous arterial channel known as the marginal artery. Vasa recta arising from the marginal arteries also supply the colon with arterial blood.
